00:17:45.430 --> 00:17:52.370
AUDIENCE: And then that omega is
also a function of [INAUDIBLE]??

00:17:52.370 --> 00:17:57.970
MICHAEL SHORT: So that omega has
some component of theta in it

00:17:57.970 --> 00:18:00.550
and some component of phi in it.

00:18:00.550 --> 00:18:02.050
Since it's a solid
angle, it depends

00:18:02.050 --> 00:18:05.530
on both the angle of rotation
and the angle of inclination,

00:18:05.530 --> 00:18:08.510
which we call theta and phi.

00:18:08.510 --> 00:18:10.930
Now to get from this to the
regular cross-section you're

00:18:10.930 --> 00:18:17.710
used to, you can integrate
over all angles omega

00:18:17.710 --> 00:18:20.592
of the differential
cross-section,

00:18:20.592 --> 00:18:22.800
and you'll get the regular
total cross-section, which

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:25.530
is just what is the probability
of Compton scattering,

00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:27.022
full stop.

00:18:27.022 --> 00:18:28.480
If you wanted to
know, then, what's

00:18:28.480 --> 00:18:32.500
the probability of Compton
scattering into this angle,

00:18:32.500 --> 00:18:33.850
it sounds kind of boring, right?

00:18:33.850 --> 00:18:35.500
Why do we care about the angle?

