00:19:51.900 --> 00:19:53.740
Interesting problem, huh?

00:19:53.740 --> 00:19:55.090
Do you just kind of look-- yeah?

00:19:55.090 --> 00:19:56.590
AUDIENCE: Do you
kind of like shield

00:19:56.590 --> 00:19:58.336
certain angles [INAUDIBLE]?

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:02.200
MICHAEL SHORT: That's one way.

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:06.880
You could mask off the ship
and move your detector around,

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:09.070
and then do it for the
other two dimensions.

00:20:09.070 --> 00:20:12.443
So that will get you
there, but slowly.

00:20:12.443 --> 00:20:13.485
How do you do it quickly?

00:20:16.670 --> 00:20:20.240
Well, you do it with the
Klein Nishina cross-section.

00:20:20.240 --> 00:20:23.060
If you know the relationship
between the energy

00:20:23.060 --> 00:20:25.280
and the angle of
a Compton scatter,

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:30.630
you take two detectors,
Detector 1, Detector 2,

00:20:30.630 --> 00:20:32.580
and you form what's
called a Compton camera.

00:20:37.550 --> 00:20:40.220
This is awesome because
with two detectors,

00:20:40.220 --> 00:20:44.390
you can pinpoint the location of
a radiation source by knowing--

00:20:44.390 --> 00:20:48.410
let's say you had a gamma
ray that entered Detector 1.

00:20:48.410 --> 00:20:50.750
So you have your
initial e gamma.

00:20:50.750 --> 00:20:52.160
And you get a spectrum.

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:54.745
Let's draw a couple of spectra.

00:20:54.745 --> 00:20:56.120
I'm going to use
different colors

00:20:56.120 --> 00:20:57.710
so I can make them bigger.

00:20:57.710 --> 00:21:03.420
This will be intensity
and this will be energy.

00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:07.130
So we have our blue
Detector 1, and we

00:21:07.130 --> 00:21:10.640
have some spectrum
for Detector 1

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:14.180
where we get the photo peak
of the gamma at e gamma.

00:21:14.180 --> 00:21:18.350
And this time, you don't
see every possible angle.

00:21:18.350 --> 00:21:23.935
You only see whatever angle you
get that Compton scatter at.

00:21:23.935 --> 00:21:26.060
Or you might see a whole
bunch of different angles.

00:21:26.060 --> 00:21:26.900
Never mind.

00:21:26.900 --> 00:21:29.250
So you're going
to see the Compton

00:21:29.250 --> 00:21:31.700
edge in this whole
continuum of things.

00:21:31.700 --> 00:21:34.100
And so you know that whatever
energy this corresponds

00:21:34.100 --> 00:21:37.040
to means that theta equals pi.

00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:41.240
That energy corresponds
to theta equals 0.

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:45.440
And you know that there's
a source somewhere in here.

00:21:45.440 --> 00:21:50.090
Now let's say that photon
scatters out of Detector 1

00:21:50.090 --> 00:21:53.690
and into Detector 2.

00:21:53.690 --> 00:21:55.610
In this case, you've
no longer just

00:21:55.610 --> 00:21:58.350
know that you have a
source of some sort.

00:21:58.350 --> 00:22:00.740
You'll end up with
a certain photo peak

00:22:00.740 --> 00:22:06.650
corresponding to this e
gamma prime, the only energy

00:22:06.650 --> 00:22:09.780
that can Compton scatter in
the direction from Detector 1

00:22:09.780 --> 00:22:12.710
to Detector 2,
because you have now

00:22:12.710 --> 00:22:16.610
determined the angles between
the line between the detectors

00:22:16.610 --> 00:22:18.540
and the detector at the source.

00:22:18.540 --> 00:22:25.770
So then you get a photo peak and
the corresponding Compton edge

00:22:25.770 --> 00:22:28.180
for your e gamma prime.

00:22:28.180 --> 00:22:32.200
Your e gamma prime, that tells
you the angle that it came off

00:22:32.200 --> 00:22:34.640
of for your first interaction.

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:39.980
So that is your source angle.

00:22:39.980 --> 00:22:43.010
So what that means is that
by using these two angles,

00:22:43.010 --> 00:22:48.930
you've now pinpointed your
source to lie somewhere

00:22:48.930 --> 00:22:57.730
on these two cones projected
back on one of the two points

00:22:57.730 --> 00:23:01.470
where those cones at
that angle intersect.

00:23:01.470 --> 00:23:03.420
This is something I want
you to try and think

00:23:03.420 --> 00:23:05.530
about and work out on your own.

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:10.292
But it's really cool to explain
this because with one detector,

00:23:10.292 --> 00:23:12.000
you know that there's
a source somewhere,

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:13.830
and you know generally
where to point.

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:17.100
With two detectors
and energy resolution,

00:23:17.100 --> 00:23:20.400
the energy of the photo
peak of the second event

00:23:20.400 --> 00:23:23.268
tells you what the angle
of the first event was.

00:23:23.268 --> 00:23:24.810
And this way, if
you know what source

00:23:24.810 --> 00:23:27.007
you're looking for from
the first photo peak,

00:23:27.007 --> 00:23:28.590
and you know what
angle you're looking

00:23:28.590 --> 00:23:32.190
for from the Compton
scattered photons photo

00:23:32.190 --> 00:23:34.950
peak, because they
have those, then you

00:23:34.950 --> 00:23:37.452
know not only what the
source is, but where it is.

00:23:37.452 --> 00:23:38.910
And you know which
container should

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:41.115
take a part to start looking.

00:23:41.115 --> 00:23:43.240
So this is why we care
about angle, because there's

00:23:43.240 --> 00:23:47.170
actual, real ways of using
this to your advantage

00:23:47.170 --> 00:23:50.390
to solve some pretty insane
problems, like which container

00:23:50.390 --> 00:23:52.500
would that be in.

00:23:52.500 --> 00:23:55.030
Who's starting to get the
general idea behind a Compton

00:23:55.030 --> 00:23:58.858
camera, or who would
like another explanation?

00:23:58.858 --> 00:24:00.713
Anyone?

00:24:00.713 --> 00:24:01.630
I asked two questions.

00:24:01.630 --> 00:24:03.682
So who would like
another explanation?

00:24:03.682 --> 00:24:05.050
Yeah, OK.

00:24:05.050 --> 00:24:07.360
The idea here is with
just one detector,

00:24:07.360 --> 00:24:09.742
all you know is whether
or not there is a source.

00:24:09.742 --> 00:24:11.200
The only information
you're getting

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:14.920
is its photo peak and
Compton edge and bowl.

00:24:14.920 --> 00:24:17.170
And so you know the
identity of the source.

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:19.180
Maybe it's cobalt
60 or something.

00:24:19.180 --> 00:24:20.950
But you don't know where it is.

00:24:20.950 --> 00:24:23.410
By making a second
measurement, you

00:24:23.410 --> 00:24:26.590
can then determine
where on the Compton

00:24:26.590 --> 00:24:29.860
spectrum of the
first measurement

00:24:29.860 --> 00:24:31.660
does the photon lie.

00:24:31.660 --> 00:24:33.910
So by saying OK, the
photo peak corresponds

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:36.490
to this energy,
which corresponds

00:24:36.490 --> 00:24:43.320
to some certain angle that
this had to scatter off of.

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:46.770
So then you know
what this angle is.

00:24:46.770 --> 00:24:49.423
You've determined theta.

00:24:49.423 --> 00:24:51.340
AUDIENCE: Is that the
same theta that you just

00:24:51.340 --> 00:24:53.248
drew as theta angle?

00:24:53.248 --> 00:24:54.040
MICHAEL SHORT: Yes.

00:24:54.040 --> 00:24:54.540
OK.

00:24:54.540 --> 00:24:56.985
Angle.

00:24:56.985 --> 00:24:58.360
You've then
determined this angle

00:24:58.360 --> 00:25:00.970
because you know the
incoming path of the photon,

00:25:00.970 --> 00:25:03.550
and you now know
the outgoing path,

00:25:03.550 --> 00:25:05.740
which means you know angle.

00:25:05.740 --> 00:25:09.220
So if you know the line
between these two detectors,

00:25:09.220 --> 00:25:13.480
and your photo pick lines
up with your first Compton

00:25:13.480 --> 00:25:18.070
spectrum's angle, you then
look at that angle back.

00:25:18.070 --> 00:25:21.040
You also have to sweep around
in the other direction, which

00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:24.220
means you end up with a
cone of possible locations.

00:25:24.220 --> 00:25:24.862
Yeah.

00:25:24.862 --> 00:25:26.612
AUDIENCE: How do you
know that the photons

00:25:26.612 --> 00:25:30.172
that get to the second scatter
from inside the first one?

00:25:30.172 --> 00:25:31.880
MICHAEL SHORT: There
can be only a couple

00:25:31.880 --> 00:25:33.890
of things that
could happen, right?

00:25:33.890 --> 00:25:35.650
You could have another
direct photon just

00:25:35.650 --> 00:25:37.880
shoot into Detector
2, in which case

00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:41.420
you'll just get a little
bit of photo peak.

00:25:41.420 --> 00:25:44.300
But we know to expect
that, so we can ignore it.

00:25:44.300 --> 00:25:47.220
We're specifically
looking for the photo peek

00:25:47.220 --> 00:25:48.940
coming from Detector 1.

00:25:48.940 --> 00:25:51.180
AUDIENCE: So they wouldn't
just go in the air

00:25:51.180 --> 00:25:53.990
and do Compton
scatter [INAUDIBLE]??

00:25:53.990 --> 00:25:57.680
MICHAEL SHORT: They would,
which gives the perfect pretext

00:25:57.680 --> 00:26:01.170
to bring up the cross-sections
for these processes.

00:26:01.170 --> 00:26:04.010
So I'm going to skip
ahead a little bit

00:26:04.010 --> 00:26:06.740
and start getting into what do
the actual cross-sections look

00:26:06.740 --> 00:26:09.830
like for Compton scattering,
photoelectric, and pair

00:26:09.830 --> 00:26:10.820
production?

00:26:10.820 --> 00:26:13.280
All of them have to
do with the electron

00:26:13.280 --> 00:26:15.350
density of the material.

00:26:15.350 --> 00:26:17.510
The more electrons
in the way, the more

00:26:17.510 --> 00:26:19.250
you get these events happening.

00:26:19.250 --> 00:26:22.040
So yes, you will get
Compton scatters in the air

00:26:22.040 --> 00:26:25.250
because air contains electrons
and they do Compton scatter.

00:26:25.250 --> 00:26:27.460
But air is not
very dense, so you

00:26:27.460 --> 00:26:28.940
will get comparatively less.

00:26:28.940 --> 00:26:33.140
So let's say that adds
a little bit of noise

00:26:33.140 --> 00:26:35.780
on the bottom, which is like
any detector spectrum we've ever

00:26:35.780 --> 00:26:36.280
seen.

00:26:36.280 --> 00:26:39.020
There's always noise from
all sorts of other processes

00:26:39.020 --> 00:26:41.030
we're not looking for.

00:26:41.030 --> 00:26:42.690
So now let's start
to look at what

00:26:42.690 --> 00:26:46.407
the general energy and z ranges
of each of these effects are.

00:26:46.407 --> 00:26:48.240
And we're going to
recreate one of the plots

00:26:48.240 --> 00:26:52.350
that I showed you at the
beginning of yesterday's class.

00:26:52.350 --> 00:26:56.100
So let's make a graph
of energy of the photon

00:26:56.100 --> 00:26:58.260
and z of the material.

00:26:58.260 --> 00:27:01.650
And we want to try to map
out where the following three

00:27:01.650 --> 00:27:03.030
processes are dominant.

00:27:03.030 --> 00:27:06.000
So tau, our
photoelectric effect.

00:27:09.910 --> 00:27:14.830
C, which we'll call
our Compton scattering.

00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:18.411
And kappa, which we'll
call pair production.

00:27:21.360 --> 00:27:24.860
And these cross-sections do
give us relative probabilities

00:27:24.860 --> 00:27:28.280
as a function of the energy
of the photon and the medium

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:30.830
they're going through, along
with the actual density,

00:27:30.830 --> 00:27:33.060
that something's
going to happen.

00:27:33.060 --> 00:27:35.110
So let's look at
the form of these.

00:27:35.110 --> 00:27:38.420
The cross-section for the
photoelectric effect scales

00:27:38.420 --> 00:27:40.840
with z to the 5th.

00:27:40.840 --> 00:27:42.430
Do you think that
photoelectric effect

00:27:42.430 --> 00:27:47.124
will be more likely for
low z or high z materials?

00:27:47.124 --> 00:27:48.110
AUDIENCE: High.

00:27:48.110 --> 00:27:49.735
MICHAEL SHORT: High
z materials, right.

00:27:49.735 --> 00:27:52.730
So we know we're going to
be in the top half area.

00:27:52.730 --> 00:27:56.575
And it scales with one
over energy to the 7/2.

00:27:56.575 --> 00:27:57.950
So do you think
this will be most

00:27:57.950 --> 00:28:00.410
likely with low or high energy?

00:28:03.320 --> 00:28:04.128
AUDIENCE: Low.

00:28:04.128 --> 00:28:05.420
MICHAEL SHORT: So lower energy.

00:28:05.420 --> 00:28:10.140
So we're going to fill in
our photoelectric somewhat.

00:28:10.140 --> 00:28:11.280
Oh, I'm sorry.

00:28:11.280 --> 00:28:13.530
So we know it's going to
be in this part of the z.

00:28:13.530 --> 00:28:15.947
We know it's going to be in
this part of the energy curve.

00:28:15.947 --> 00:28:21.320
So let's fill in that
area as photoelectric.

00:28:21.320 --> 00:28:24.450
Let's look at the other
extreme, pair production.

00:28:24.450 --> 00:28:26.300
It scales with z
squared, so is that

00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:28.130
going to be in the low
or the high z area?

00:28:36.460 --> 00:28:37.450
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:37.450 --> 00:28:38.610
MICHAEL SHORT: I
think still high,

00:28:38.610 --> 00:28:40.440
just the bigger the z, the
bigger the cross-section,

00:28:40.440 --> 00:28:41.100
right?

00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:42.540
So we know that
pair production is

00:28:42.540 --> 00:28:44.220
going to be in the high z area.

00:28:44.220 --> 00:28:46.780
Now how about the energy?

00:28:46.780 --> 00:28:48.850
It scales with
the log of energy,

00:28:48.850 --> 00:28:50.530
but the energy is on the top.

00:28:50.530 --> 00:28:54.740
So will a low or a high energy
give you more pair production?

00:28:54.740 --> 00:28:55.240
High.

00:28:55.240 --> 00:28:59.110
So pair production
is going to be here,

00:28:59.110 --> 00:29:04.440
leaving everything else
for Compton scattering.

00:29:04.440 --> 00:29:09.020
And if we jump back to
the start of last class,

00:29:09.020 --> 00:29:12.260
we've reproduced from the
cross-sections the same sort

00:29:12.260 --> 00:29:16.210
of plot that we saw
before just from looking

00:29:16.210 --> 00:29:20.450
at the relative probabilities
of each effect, which

00:29:20.450 --> 00:29:22.160
I think it's pretty cool.

00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:26.100
We can now do that with some
basic physics knowledge.

00:29:26.100 --> 00:29:29.070
Last thing I want to fill in
for Compton scattering is that

00:29:29.070 --> 00:29:35.400
the Klein Nishina cross-section,
which is your differential

00:29:35.400 --> 00:29:38.310
cross-section as a
function of omega,

00:29:38.310 --> 00:29:44.520
combined with the probability
that you scatter into a certain

00:29:44.520 --> 00:29:48.910
angle and a certain energy--
because there's a one-to-one

00:29:48.910 --> 00:29:50.530
relationship--

00:29:50.530 --> 00:29:52.690
ends up giving
you your d sigma c

00:29:52.690 --> 00:29:58.030
over de, which is your energy
distribution of Compton recoil

00:29:58.030 --> 00:29:59.380
electrons.

00:29:59.380 --> 00:30:02.490
And that's directly what
leads to the shape right here,

00:30:02.490 --> 00:30:05.650
where if you have,
let's say, 0.51 MeV,

00:30:05.650 --> 00:30:08.810
relatively low energy, there's--

00:30:08.810 --> 00:30:11.210
let's see.

00:30:11.210 --> 00:30:13.650
What do I want to say here?

00:30:13.650 --> 00:30:14.150
Yeah.

00:30:14.150 --> 00:30:17.240
So as you go up in
higher and higher energy,

00:30:17.240 --> 00:30:19.340
you get fewer and fewer
Compton electrons,

00:30:19.340 --> 00:30:22.190
because like Jared was
saying, the probability

00:30:22.190 --> 00:30:23.870
of a Compton
interaction does go down

00:30:23.870 --> 00:30:26.900
with increasing energy, as
we kind of reasoned out.

00:30:26.900 --> 00:30:31.190
But in addition, you
get relatively more

00:30:31.190 --> 00:30:34.880
of these back scattered ones,
which is kind of interesting.

00:30:34.880 --> 00:30:36.308
I have to think about that one.

00:30:36.308 --> 00:30:38.100
But this is the typical
shape that you tend

00:30:38.100 --> 00:30:40.680
to see for Compton scattering.

00:30:40.680 --> 00:30:43.560
For high energy photons, you
get a Compton peak and then

00:30:43.560 --> 00:30:46.830
a very long, shallow tail.

00:30:46.830 --> 00:30:49.010
And as you go lower
and lower energy,

00:30:49.010 --> 00:30:50.900
it starts to sort
of bounce back up.

00:30:50.900 --> 00:30:52.650
And yeah, Luke?

00:30:52.650 --> 00:30:54.840
AUDIENCE: When Compton
scattering happens,

00:30:54.840 --> 00:30:57.230
are the electrons being
knocked off the atom?

00:30:57.230 --> 00:30:58.230
MICHAEL SHORT: Oh, yeah.

00:30:58.230 --> 00:30:58.772
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:30:58.772 --> 00:31:01.160
So how is that different from
the photoelectric effect?

00:31:01.160 --> 00:31:02.785
MICHAEL SHORT: The
photoelectric effect

00:31:02.785 --> 00:31:04.920
is an absorption
followed by an injection.

00:31:04.920 --> 00:31:08.250
In Compton scattering, the
other photon is still intact.

00:31:08.250 --> 00:31:11.880
It just loses energy,
gains wavelength.

00:31:11.880 --> 00:31:14.700
But the energy of Compton
scattering is-- let's say,

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:18.120
for MeV photons, it's on the
order of hundreds of keV--

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:21.298
plenty to eject most of
the electrons from an atom.

00:31:21.298 --> 00:31:22.840
So you always have
to think about are

00:31:22.840 --> 00:31:24.250
you going to eject something?

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:26.200
Are you above the work function?

00:31:26.200 --> 00:31:28.290
Work function for most atoms--

00:31:28.290 --> 00:31:30.230
so we had a nice plot of that--

00:31:30.230 --> 00:31:32.140
is in the eV range.

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:34.300
So chances are, yeah,
Compton scattering mostly

00:31:34.300 --> 00:31:36.280
is going to be ejecting
electrons, too.

00:31:36.280 --> 00:31:38.350
That's the whole reason
we can count them.

00:31:38.350 --> 00:31:40.450
If there wasn't an
electron ejection,

00:31:40.450 --> 00:31:45.300
there would be no electron
ionization cascade to count.

00:31:45.300 --> 00:31:47.880
So there's some sort of
empirical or experimental proof

00:31:47.880 --> 00:31:49.670
that it does happen.

00:31:49.670 --> 00:31:52.130
And speaking of
experimental proof,

00:31:52.130 --> 00:31:53.720
you can actually see that shape.

00:31:53.720 --> 00:31:57.470
In this case, this is a spectrum
taken from two different gamma

00:31:57.470 --> 00:32:02.900
sources together, a-- what is
it, 1.28 MeV and a 0.51 Mev.

00:32:02.900 --> 00:32:05.270
And you can see that the
1.28 MeV, first of all,

00:32:05.270 --> 00:32:07.730
has a way lower
number of counts,

00:32:07.730 --> 00:32:09.650
showing that the
cross-section does,

00:32:09.650 --> 00:32:12.500
indeed, decrease
with higher energy.

00:32:12.500 --> 00:32:15.210
And it doesn't have-- well,
you can't really even see--

00:32:15.210 --> 00:32:18.620
but it does not curving
back up, whereas this lower

00:32:18.620 --> 00:32:21.230
energy Compton
photon is scattering

00:32:21.230 --> 00:32:23.630
more often because
it's much higher,

00:32:23.630 --> 00:32:28.273
and it's got that bump back
up at the really low energies.

00:32:28.273 --> 00:32:29.690
So it's kind of
neat when the math

00:32:29.690 --> 00:32:33.230
that we're looking at, if I jump
ahead to the cross-sections,

00:32:33.230 --> 00:32:36.770
you can see that you'd
expect the Compton scattering

00:32:36.770 --> 00:32:38.800
to decrease with energy.

00:32:38.800 --> 00:32:42.650
And you look at an experimental
plot of two different energies,

00:32:42.650 --> 00:32:45.000
and there you have
it, higher energy,

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:49.060
less total Compton scattering,
but different shape.

00:32:51.890 --> 00:32:53.900
So any questions before
I move on to how you can

00:32:53.900 --> 00:32:55.618
use them to design shielding?

00:33:01.970 --> 00:33:04.940
So what we're getting
here, these cross-sections,

00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:07.220
are probably better
known to some of you

00:33:07.220 --> 00:33:10.280
as mass attenuation
coefficients, which

00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:14.600
are simpler ways of
describing how many photons

00:33:14.600 --> 00:33:18.410
in a narrow beam would
undergo some sort of process

00:33:18.410 --> 00:33:20.570
and be removed from the beam.

00:33:20.570 --> 00:33:22.670
And they get removed
exponentially

00:33:22.670 --> 00:33:25.070
for the same sort of reason
for pretty much everything

00:33:25.070 --> 00:33:27.710
in this class ends up being
an exponential, doesn't it?

00:33:27.710 --> 00:33:33.080
Where if you have some
intensity of photons

00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:35.300
or some change in
intensity that's

00:33:35.300 --> 00:33:40.080
proportional to a change
in x in the initial--

00:33:40.080 --> 00:33:42.610
let's see-- and some--

00:33:42.610 --> 00:33:45.460
what is it, concept
of proportionality

00:33:45.460 --> 00:33:48.580
like the cross-section,
or we'll call it now mu,

00:33:48.580 --> 00:33:50.890
this mass attenuation
coefficient.

00:33:50.890 --> 00:33:53.140
The answer to that ends up
being pretty much the same.

00:33:56.180 --> 00:33:58.520
And it's this simple
exponential thing.

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:00.035
And the nice thing
is you don't have

00:34:00.035 --> 00:34:02.660
to calculate all these different
cross-sections because they're

00:34:02.660 --> 00:34:05.330
tabulated for you by NIST.

00:34:05.330 --> 00:34:07.190
And that's one of the
links on the website,

00:34:07.190 --> 00:34:09.815
on the learning modules website
that I want to show to you guys

00:34:09.815 --> 00:34:10.639
now.

00:34:10.639 --> 00:34:14.090
You can actually look up these
total summed cross-sections

00:34:14.090 --> 00:34:16.489
for gamma ray
interactions as a function

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:19.850
of energy versus their mass
attenuation coefficient

00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:22.883
in centimeters squared per gram.

00:34:22.883 --> 00:34:24.300
The reason it's
in that unit is it

00:34:24.300 --> 00:34:26.880
just tells you what
the material does.

00:34:26.880 --> 00:34:29.330
It doesn't tell you how
much you have in the way.

00:34:29.330 --> 00:34:33.409
And that's why I've rewritten
this exponential attenuation

00:34:33.409 --> 00:34:36.260
formula with a rho on
the bottom and a rho

00:34:36.260 --> 00:34:39.409
on the top, that rho being
the density of the material

00:34:39.409 --> 00:34:42.590
because usually you can just
say, it's like i naught e

00:34:42.590 --> 00:34:44.030
to the mu x.

00:34:44.030 --> 00:34:46.940
But these are the things that
you'll look up in tables.

00:34:46.940 --> 00:34:49.370
And these rhos right
here is whatever density

00:34:49.370 --> 00:34:51.239
you have of your material.

00:34:51.239 --> 00:34:54.710
So if you want to calculate
how much better cold water is

00:34:54.710 --> 00:34:58.280
shielding than hot water because
of its change in density,

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:00.845
you can then look up
the value for water,

00:35:00.845 --> 00:35:02.720
which I want to show
you how to do right now.

00:35:06.460 --> 00:35:10.090
Back up to see the actual site.

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:12.450
So if you guys looked
right here, these--

00:35:12.450 --> 00:35:13.350
what is it--

00:35:13.350 --> 00:35:15.987
NIST tables of x-ray
absorption coefficients.

00:35:15.987 --> 00:35:17.820
I'll show you how to
read through this table

00:35:17.820 --> 00:35:20.640
now because you'll need it from
everything from problem set 5

00:35:20.640 --> 00:35:21.930
to the rest of your life.

00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:24.750
This is one of those places
you're going to go constantly

00:35:24.750 --> 00:35:27.570
looking for nuclear data.

00:35:27.570 --> 00:35:30.185
So you can either look
at elemental media

00:35:30.185 --> 00:35:32.310
or compounds and mixtures,
water being one of them.

00:35:34.960 --> 00:35:39.570
So let's go down
to water, liquid.

00:35:39.570 --> 00:35:41.280
If you notice what's
actually given here

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:43.470
is this view over row.

00:35:43.470 --> 00:35:45.510
So the nasty, what
is it, density

00:35:45.510 --> 00:35:48.820
specific mass
attenuation coefficient.

00:35:48.820 --> 00:35:51.520
In other words, it's a
cross-section, really.

00:35:51.520 --> 00:35:53.317
It's a microscopic
cross-section.

00:35:53.317 --> 00:35:55.150
I don't know why, in a
lot of these courses,

00:35:55.150 --> 00:35:57.730
they're introduced separately
because they're the same thing.

00:35:57.730 --> 00:35:59.860
They're interaction
probabilities.

00:35:59.860 --> 00:36:02.477
And then that other
rho from the slides

00:36:02.477 --> 00:36:04.060
just tells you how
much is in the way.

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:06.460
That rho times x just
tells you how much

00:36:06.460 --> 00:36:09.850
water's in the way in
terms of how dense it is

00:36:09.850 --> 00:36:12.760
and how thick your
water shield is.

00:36:12.760 --> 00:36:15.250
So using these tables,
if you know, let's say,

00:36:15.250 --> 00:36:17.330
you're sending in
one MeV photon,

00:36:17.330 --> 00:36:20.380
so we look up 10 to the 0 MeV--

00:36:20.380 --> 00:36:23.080
you then have this value,
this nice round value of 10

00:36:23.080 --> 00:36:27.120
to the minus 1 centimeters
squared per gram.

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:29.170
You then multiply by
the density of the water

00:36:29.170 --> 00:36:32.230
that you have multiplied by
the thickness of your water

00:36:32.230 --> 00:36:34.090
shielding, and
you get the change

00:36:34.090 --> 00:36:36.570
in intensity of the photons.

00:36:36.570 --> 00:36:39.160
And let's do an example
calculation just

00:36:39.160 --> 00:36:41.760
to make it a little more real.

00:36:41.760 --> 00:36:47.600
So let's say we have a beam of
photons of intensity i naught.

00:36:47.600 --> 00:36:51.650
And we're sending it
through a tank of water.

00:36:51.650 --> 00:36:54.680
And the question is, do you want
to keep this water at 0 Celsius

00:36:54.680 --> 00:36:55.625
or at 100 Celsius?

00:37:01.480 --> 00:37:04.270
What's the difference in
shielding between freezing

00:37:04.270 --> 00:37:06.250
and boiling liquid water?

00:37:06.250 --> 00:37:08.200
Well, we can look that up.

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:10.820
And let's say we have to specify
an energy of the photons.

00:37:10.820 --> 00:37:14.040
We'll call it 1 MeV photons.

00:37:14.040 --> 00:37:19.970
So we can look up and say at
10 to the 0 MeV, we go over.

00:37:19.970 --> 00:37:23.870
We get just about
0.1 mu over rho.

00:37:23.870 --> 00:37:32.930
So mu over rho equals 0.1
centimeters squared per gram.

00:37:32.930 --> 00:37:36.530
And now we can set up two
equations, one for 0 Celsius

00:37:36.530 --> 00:37:38.850
and one for 100 Celsius.

00:37:38.850 --> 00:37:42.770
So we'll say i at 0
C equals i naught.

00:37:42.770 --> 00:37:49.880
E to the minus 0.1 times
rho at 0 Celsius times x.

00:37:49.880 --> 00:37:53.140
Let's say we have, I don't
know, 10 centimeters of water.

00:37:56.290 --> 00:37:58.170
So we'll just put a 10 in there.

00:37:58.170 --> 00:38:01.350
That works out pretty well.

00:38:01.350 --> 00:38:07.410
And then our i at 100C is
the same i naught times e

00:38:07.410 --> 00:38:11.280
to the minus 0.1
times rho of water

00:38:11.280 --> 00:38:14.813
at 100 times 10 centimeters.

00:38:14.813 --> 00:38:16.230
And keep in mind
here, I made sure

00:38:16.230 --> 00:38:20.700
that since my mu over rho units
are in centimeters squared

00:38:20.700 --> 00:38:23.970
per gram, I'm putting
in x as 10 centimeters

00:38:23.970 --> 00:38:27.635
because whatever is up
here in the exponential has

00:38:27.635 --> 00:38:28.260
to be unitless.

00:38:31.110 --> 00:38:33.420
That's a good check to see
why are my calculations off

00:38:33.420 --> 00:38:35.290
by a factor of a billion?

00:38:35.290 --> 00:38:38.500
Just check the units
in the exponential.

00:38:38.500 --> 00:38:39.020
Yeah.

00:38:39.020 --> 00:38:42.620
AUDIENCE: Wouldn't the
value of 0.1 change

00:38:42.620 --> 00:38:47.090
for your cross-section
[INAUDIBLE]??

00:38:47.090 --> 00:38:48.590
MICHAEL SHORT: The
value of 0.1 will

00:38:48.590 --> 00:38:51.680
change depending on the energy
