00:38:51.680 --> 00:38:53.340
AUDIENCE: I mean,
for the density.

00:38:53.340 --> 00:38:53.850
MICHAEL SHORT: Nope.

00:38:53.850 --> 00:38:55.160
AUDIENCE: Density
changes, right?

00:38:55.160 --> 00:38:56.452
MICHAEL SHORT: Density changes.

00:38:56.452 --> 00:38:59.400
And that's what we account
for here with this rho.

00:38:59.400 --> 00:39:01.700
So next up we have to look
up the densities of water

00:39:01.700 --> 00:39:04.470
at 0 and 100 Celsius because
I don't actually know them.

00:39:09.280 --> 00:39:11.120
So density of water at 0C--

00:39:11.120 --> 00:39:13.520
oh, surprise,
surprise-- it's we'll

00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:17.102
call it 1 gram per
centimeter cubed.

00:39:17.102 --> 00:39:18.060
Now what is it at 100C?

00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:28.540
Too close to tell.

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:29.040
Actually.

00:39:29.040 --> 00:39:29.832
That's interesting.

00:39:29.832 --> 00:39:33.120
At 0 it's a little lower.

