00:42:50.030 --> 00:42:52.680
For lead, it's like 80 keV.

00:42:52.680 --> 00:42:57.540
For tin, it's probably
more like 50 keV.

00:42:57.540 --> 00:43:01.015
It's decreasing with z.

00:43:01.015 --> 00:43:02.640
Anyone remember what
sort of magnitude?

00:43:02.640 --> 00:43:06.000
We've looked at things
like this before.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:09.360
And if we're talking about
photon electron interactions,

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:12.020
what could be responsible for
those sudden jagged edges?

00:43:22.330 --> 00:43:24.880
Well, we have talked
before about all sorts

00:43:24.880 --> 00:43:27.310
of different decay
methods, including

00:43:27.310 --> 00:43:31.090
those that can eject electrons
from different energy shells.

00:43:31.090 --> 00:43:34.210
You're looking at the same
electron energy shells.

00:43:34.210 --> 00:43:38.710
If you have a, let's say,
photoelectric capable photon

00:43:38.710 --> 00:43:41.530
entering a calcium
nucleus-- and let's go look

00:43:41.530 --> 00:43:44.370
at calcium as an example.

00:43:44.370 --> 00:43:47.110
So I'll go to the
tables of coefficients.

00:43:47.110 --> 00:43:51.240
I'm going to back up
to elemental media.

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:54.130
And I'm going to go to
calcium for a simple example.

00:43:54.130 --> 00:43:57.490
Calcium has got this
jagged edge right here.

00:43:57.490 --> 00:44:04.290
And if we draw a line down,
