00:44:04.290 --> 00:44:08.370
4 keV, I bet, is
going to be the k edge

00:44:08.370 --> 00:44:12.600
energy, the energy of the most
inner bound calcium electron.

00:44:12.600 --> 00:44:14.550
To find out, we can go
to the other NIST page

00:44:14.550 --> 00:44:18.480
that I linked you guys to, the
NIST X-ray Transition Energy

00:44:18.480 --> 00:44:20.040
Table.

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:21.325
And let's look at calcium.

00:44:24.550 --> 00:44:27.760
Wow, this really doesn't work
with chalk on your fingers.

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:31.170
And let's look at
the k edge to check.

00:44:31.170 --> 00:44:32.160
Lo and behold.

00:44:32.160 --> 00:44:35.700
4.05 keV.

00:44:35.700 --> 00:44:40.740
So what you're seeing here is
the photoelectric peak k edge

00:44:40.740 --> 00:44:41.850
absorption.

00:44:41.850 --> 00:44:45.480
What this says is at
energies below 4 keV,

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:48.450
you can't inject the
innermost electron.

00:44:48.450 --> 00:44:50.430
You just don't
have enough energy.

00:44:50.430 --> 00:44:53.790
As soon as you hit 4 keV,
those inner shell electrons

00:44:53.790 --> 00:44:55.470
become accessible to you.

00:44:55.470 --> 00:44:57.840
So the cross-section
suddenly jumps up

00:44:57.840 --> 00:44:59.910
because you have more
electrons that you

00:44:59.910 --> 00:45:02.220
can inject photoelectrically.

00:45:02.220 --> 00:45:05.640
Beyond 100 keV or so,
there's no more jagged edges

00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:09.960
because any photon above 100
keV can access pretty much

00:45:09.960 --> 00:45:12.570
any electron in any
element, except maybe

00:45:12.570 --> 00:45:16.250
the super heavy ones, and we
don't have data for them yet.

00:45:16.250 --> 00:45:18.140
So then you might ask,
